---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import ReplyTask from '../../../../../components/ReplyTask.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';

const endpointCode = `app.MapPost("/users", async (
    CreateUserRequest request,
    AppDbContext db,
    CancellationToken cancellationToken) =>
{
    var exists = await db.Users.AnyAsync(
        user => user.Email == request.Email,
        cancellationToken);

    if (exists)
    {
        return Results.Conflict(new { error = "Email is already in use." });
    }

    db.Users.Add(new User { Email = request.Email });
    await db.SaveChangesAsync(cancellationToken);

    return Results.Created($"/users/{request.Email}", new { request.Email });
});`;

const timeline = `Request A: AnyAsync(email) → false
Request B: AnyAsync(email) → false
Request A: SaveChangesAsync() → succeeds
Request B: SaveChangesAsync() → database unique constraint fails`;

---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 8 · .NET: race-safe uniqueness"
  heading="Review a duplicate-email endpoint under concurrent requests"
  lede="A friendly pre-check can improve the normal response, but it cannot make a uniqueness guarantee. Trace the race, choose the authoritative layer, and sketch a production-safe response path."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="The tempting endpoint">
    <Code code={endpointCode} lang="csharp" />
    <p>On its own, this looks reasonable: it checks for an existing email, returns <code>409 Conflict</code> when it finds one, then inserts the new user.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The gap between check and write">
    <Code code={timeline} lang="text" />
    <Callout>
      Two requests can both read “no user yet” before either one writes. The application-level pre-check is useful for the common case, but it is not a concurrency guarantee.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="A reliable boundary">
    <ul>
      <li>Put a unique constraint or unique index on the email column in the database.</li>
      <li>Keep the pre-check only as an optional fast path and user-friendly response.</li>
      <li>At the write boundary, catch and recognize the database’s unique-constraint failure, then translate that expected conflict to <code>409 Conflict</code>.</li>
      <li>Let the request <code>CancellationToken</code> flow to async database work. Do not turn client cancellation into a fake duplicate-email response.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The exact exception type and constraint inspection are database-provider-specific. That detail belongs behind a small, tested translation boundary rather than scattered through endpoint code.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:dotnet/008:q1" difficulty={4}>
    <p>Review this as a backend engineer. Explain the race, identify the real uniqueness authority, then propose a concise production approach.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Explain how both reads can say “not found.”</li>
      <li>Choose the final enforcement layer and the deliberate HTTP result for the raced duplicate.</li>
      <li>Outline the database rule, exception translation boundary, and cancellation behavior.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>You do not need a full project or provider-specific error numbers. Precision about responsibilities matters more than syntax.</p>
  </ReplyTask>
</SessionPage>
